---
// src/pages/projects/example-project.astro
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Belt-driven pen plotter — Nicholas Surname">
  <article class="project-page">
    <header class="project-header">
      <p class="label">PB-001 · Personal Build</p>
      <h1>Belt-driven pen plotter</h1>
      <p class="project-lede">
        A CoreXY plotter designed from scratch: custom extrusion frame, printed
        motion components, and a small G-code sender written in Python.
      </p>
      <p class="label project-facts">
        2025 · Fusion 360 · FDM printing · Python
      </p>
    </header>

    <!--
      Images: drop files into the /public folder of your project, e.g.
      public/projects/plotter/render-01.jpg, then reference them from the
      site root like below. Delete this placeholder block once you have
      real images.
    -->
    <figure class="project-figure">
      <div class="img-placeholder" aria-hidden="true">
        RENDER — ISO VIEW (replace with your image)
      </div>
      <!-- <img src="/projects/plotter/render-01.jpg" alt="Isometric CAD render of the plotter frame" /> -->
      <figcaption class="label">FIG. 1 — Isometric render, rev C frame</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A few sentences on what the project is, why you built it, and what the
      end result was. Lead with the outcome — what it does, what it achieved —
      before the process.
    </p>

    <h2>Design</h2>
    <p>
      Walk through the interesting decisions: why CoreXY over cartesian, how
      the belt tensioning works, what failed in rev A and what changed in rev
      B. This is the part that makes a portfolio more than a resume — show
      your reasoning, not just the finished part.
    </p>

    <figure class="project-figure">
      <div class="img-placeholder" aria-hidden="true">
        PHOTO — ASSEMBLED MACHINE (replace with your image)
      </div>
      <figcaption class="label">FIG. 2 — Assembled machine, first plot</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Results</h2>
    <p>
      Quantify where you can: positional repeatability, print time, cost,
      cycle counts. Numbers read as engineering; adjectives read as marketing.
    </p>

    <p class="back-link"><a href="/">← Back to index</a></p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .project-page {
    padding: 4rem 0 1rem;
  }

  .project-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .project-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.4rem);
    margin-top: 1rem;
  }

  .project-lede {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
    max-width: 52ch;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
  }

  .project-facts {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
  }

  .project-page h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .project-figure {
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
  }

  .project-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.6rem;
  }

  .img-placeholder {
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-strong);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    text-align: center;
    padding: 1rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    margin-top: 3.5rem;
  }
</style>